  abstract={Pcf11 is one of numerous proteins involved in {pre-mRNA} 3'-end processing and transcription termination. Using elongation complexes {(ECs)} formed from purified yeast {RNA} polymerase {II} {(Pol} {II),} we show that a 140-amino acid polypeptide from yeast Pcf11 is capable of dismantling the {EC} in vitro. This action depends on the C-terminal domain {(CTD)} of the largest subunit of Pol {II} and the {CTD-interaction} domain {(CID)} of Pcf11. Our experiments reveal a novel termination mechanism whereby Pcf11 bridges the {CTD} to the nascent transcript and causes dissociation of both Pol {II} and the nascent transcript from the {DNA} in the absence of nucleotide hydrolysis. We posit that conformational changes in the {CTD} are transduced through Pcf11 to the nascent transcript to cause termination.},
