  abstract={Every nucleosome across the genome must be disrupted and reformed when the replication fork passes, but how chromatin organization is re-established following replication is unknown. To address this problem, we have developed Mapping {In\&\#xA0;vivo} Nascent Chromatin with {EdU} and sequencing {(MINCE-seq)} to characterize the genome-wide location of nucleosomes and other chromatin proteins behind replication forks at high temporal and spatial resolution. We find that the characteristic chromatin landscape at Drosophila promoters and enhancers is lost upon replication. The most conspicuous changes are at promoters that have high levels of {RNA} polymerase {II} {(RNAPII)} stalling and {DNA} accessibility and show specific enrichment for the {BRM} remodeler. Enhancer chromatin is also disrupted during replication, suggesting a role for transcription factor {(TF)} competition in nucleosome re-establishment. Thus, the characteristic nucleosome landscape emerges from a uniformly packaged genome by the action of {TFs,} {RNAPII,} and remodelers minutes after replication fork passage.},
